stoms and traditions from everyday home life, but also through the frequent elision of regional and confessional differences. Following the groundbreaking work of Anne Applebaum’s Gulag: A History (2003), this book is a must-read for anyone interested in gendered strategies of survival, accommodation, and resistance to the dehumanizing effects of the Gulag.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aInternment campszSoviet Union. 0aPrisonerszSoviet Union. 0aPrisonerszUkraine. 0aPrisonszSoviet Union. 0aWomen internment camp inmateszSoviet Union. 0aWomen internment camp inmateszUkraine. 0aWomen internment camp inmates. 0aWomen prisonerszSoviet Union. 0aWomen prisonerszUkraine. 0aWomen, UkrainianzSoviet Union. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067425834140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674258341423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674258341/original  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK